# Containerizer + SDK

## Containerizer image builder

### Default ports used

They can be changed inside the [Dockerfile](./Dockerfile):

- PROXY_PORT: 5000
- KFSERVING_PORT: 8081

### Build and run Kaniko service

```
$> docker build -f ./builder_service/Dockerfile -t kaniko ./builder_service
$> docker run -d --rm --name kaniko_container -p 5000:5000 kaniko
```

### Build and run sklearn model image

```
$> cd ./builder_service/test/sklearn
$> zip -jr model.zip ./example_model
$> tar_path=$(curl -X POST -F "body=@body.json;type=application/json" -F "model=@model.zip" localhost:5000/build | jq -r '.tar_path')
$> docker cp kaniko_container:"$tar_path" ./sklearn_kaniko_image.tar
$> docker load --input sklearn_kaniko_image.tar
$> docker run --rm --name sklearnserver -p 3000:5000 -v $PWD/data:/input -v $PWD/output:/output kaniko_image_sklearn
```

### Try Modzy endpoints

```
$> curl -X GET localhost:3000/
$> curl -X GET localhost:3000/status
$> curl -X POST -d '{ "type": "file", "input": "/input", "output": "/output" }' localhost:3000/run
$> curl -X POST localhost:3000/shutdown
```

## Containerizer SDK

### Installation

```
$> cd ./containerizer-model-sdk
$> pip3 install .
```

### Default values

If you are not going to deploy the container, you only need to specify the `name` and the `version`, as shown in the following example:

```
(...)
data = {
    'name': test-sklearn,
    'version': 0.0.1
}

modzymodel.publish(
    values=data,
    input_example_path=input_file,
    deploy=False
)
```

When deploying the container, you should fill in all the values that are also requested across the UI. There are several values that are set to defaults and can be overwritten:

```
{
    'description': 'Example of short description.',
    'longDescription': 'Example of long description.',
    'performanceSummary': 'Example of performance summary.',
    'requirement': {
      'cpuAmount': '1000m',
      'gpuUnits': 0,
      'memoryAmount': '512Mi'
    },
    'technicalDetails': 'Example of technical details.',
    'timeout': {
      'run': 30000,
      'status': 30000
    },
    'tags': [{'name': 'Label or Classify'}, {'name': 'Language and Text'}, {'name': 'Image'}],
    'versionHistory': 'Example of version history.'
}
```

So this is an example of the minimum values required to deploy the container. The values not defined here will be set to defaults:

```
(...)

data = {
    'name': 'test-sklearn',
    'version': '0.0.1',
    'inputs': [{'name': 'digit.jpg', 'description': 'description input', 'acceptedMediaTypes': 'image/jpeg', 'maximumSize': int(1.024e6)}],
    'outputs': [{'name': 'digit.jpg.json', 'description': 'description output', 'mediaType': 'application/json', 'maximumSize': int(1.024e6)}],
}

modzymodel.publish(
    values=data,
    input_example_path=input_file,
    deploy=True
)
```

#### Inputs and outputs

If you use the option `deploy=True`, `inputs` and `outputs` are required since they are used during the deployment of the container.

For every input there must be one output of type `json`. The `name` of every output must be the same as the referenced input but it must ends with the extension `.json`. E.g.: if the input name is `digit.jpg` its corresponding output name should be `digit.jpg.json`. Job input names must match this name.

If you decide not to deploy the container using the option `deploy=False` you will need to define inputs and outputs from the UI following the same instructions explained above.

### Run a job

This is an example of the required data to run a job of type `embedded`:

```
request_data = {
  'model': {
    'identifier': f'{model_data.get("identifier")}',
    'version': f'{model_data.get("version")}'
  },
  'input': {
    'type': 'embedded',
    'sources': {
      'image-1': {
        'digit.jpg': 'data:image/jpeg;base64,'
      }
    }
  }
}
```

As can be seen, `sources` field contains all the input to be processed. In this example, `image-1` is the reference of the input and `digit.jpg` is the input name, which matches the input name defined in the container.

For more information about embedded inputs you can go to [Modzy API - Job embedded](https://master.dev.modzy.engineering/docs/jobs/jobs/submit-job-embedded).

On the other hand, if you want to use text because that is what your model expects you should encapsulate it inside a stringified json within the key `instances`:

```
"{ 'instances': [<your_data_here>] }"
```
